  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Suppose that <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m> are vectors where
	<me>
	  \vvec\cdot\vvec = 4, \hspace{24pt}
	  \wvec\cdot\wvec = 20,\hspace{24pt}
	  \vvec\cdot\wvec=8.
	</me>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What is <m>\len{\vvec}</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What is the angle between <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that <m>t</m> is a scalar.  Find the value of
	      <m>t</m> for which <m>\vvec</m> is orthogonal to
	      <m>\wvec+t\vvec</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\len{\vvec} = \sqrt{\vvec\cdot\vvec} = 2</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\theta =
	      \arccos\left(\frac{\vvec\cdot\wvec}{\len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}}\right)
	      = 26.6^\circ</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>(\wvec+t\vvec)\cdot\vvec = 8 + 4t = 0</m> so
	      <m>t=-2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>2</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\theta
	      = 26.6^\circ</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>t=-2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Suppose that <m>\vvec=3\wvec</m>.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What is the relationship
	      between <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec</m> and
	      <m>\wvec\cdot\wvec</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What is the relationship between <m>\len{\vvec}</m> and
	      <m>\len{\wvec}</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>\vvec=s\wvec</m> for some scalar <m>s</m>, what is
	      the relationship between <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec</m> and
	      <m>\wvec\cdot\wvec</m>?  What is the relationship
	      between <m>\len{\vvec}</m> and <m>\len{\wvec}</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that <m>\vvec=\threevec{3}{-2}2</m>.  Find a
	      scalar <m>s</m> so that <m>s\vvec</m> has length 1.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec = (3\wvec)\cdot(3\wvec) =
	      9\wvec\cdot\wvec</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\len{\vvec} = \sqrt{\vvec\cdot\vvec} =
	      3\sqrt{\wvec\cdot\wvec} = 3\len{\wvec}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec = s^2\wvec\cdot\wvec</m> so that
	      <m>\len{\vvec} = |s|\len{\wvec}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      We know <m>\len{s\vvec} = s\len{\vvec} = s\sqrt{17} =
	      1</m> so <m>s=1/\sqrt{17}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec = 
	      9\wvec\cdot\wvec</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\len{\vvec} = 3\len{\wvec}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\len{\vvec} = |s|\len{\wvec}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>s=1/\sqrt{17}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
	      
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Given vectors <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m>, explain why
	<me>
	  \len{\vvec+\wvec}^2 + \len{\vvec-\wvec}^2 = 2\len{\vvec}^2 +
	  2\len{\wvec}^2.
	</me>
	Sketch two vectors <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m> and explain
	why this fact is called the <em>parallelogram law</em>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	<md>
	  <mrow>
	    \len{\vvec+\wvec}^2 + \len{\vvec-\wvec}^2 
	    {}={} \amp (\vvec+\wvec)\cdot(\vvec+\wvec) + 	  
	    (\vvec-\wvec)\cdot(\vvec-\wvec)
	  </mrow>
	  <mrow>
	    {}={} \amp \vvec\cdot\vvec+2\vvec\cdot\wvec + \wvec\cdot\wvec + 
	    \vvec\cdot\vvec-2\vvec\cdot\wvec + \wvec\cdot\wvec
	  </mrow>
	  <mrow>
	    {}={} \amp 2\vvec\cdot\vvec + 2\wvec\cdot\wvec
	  </mrow>
	  <mrow>
	    {}={} \amp 2\len{\vvec}^2 + 2\len{\wvec}^2
	  </mrow>
	</md>
      </p>
      <sidebyside width="50%">
	<image source="images/parallelogram-law" />
      </sidebyside>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	Use the relationship <m>\len{\uvec}^2 = \uvec\cdot\uvec</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside width="50%">
	<image source="images/parallelogram-law" />
      </sidebyside>
    </answer>
	  
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Consider the vectors
	<me>
	  \vvec_1=\threevec204,\hspace{24pt}
	  \vvec_2=\threevec{-1}2{-4}.
	</me>
	and a general vector <m>\xvec=\threevec xyz</m>.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Write an equation in terms of <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and
	      <m>z</m> that describes all the vectors <m>\xvec</m>
	      orthogonal to <m>\vvec_1</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Write a linear system that describes all the vectors
	      <m>\xvec</m> orthogonal to both <m>\vvec_1</m> and
	      <m>\vvec_2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Write the solution set to this linear system in
	      parametric form.  What type of geometric object does
	      this solution set represent?  Indicate with a rough
	      sketch why this makes sense.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Give a parametric description of all vectors orthogonal
	      to <m>\vvec_1</m>.  What type of geometric object does
	      this represent?  Indicate with a rough sketch why this
	      makes sense.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec\cdot\xvec = 2x + 4z = 0</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <md>
		<mrow>
		  2x + 4z {}={} 0 
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
		  -x+2y-4z {}={} 0
		</mrow>
	      </md>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\xvec = x_3\threevec{-2}{1}1</m>, which describes a
	      line
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\xvec = x_2\threevec{0}{1}{0} +
	      x_3\threevec{-2}01</m>, which describes a plane.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>2x + 4z = 0</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <md>
		<mrow>
		  2x + 4z {}={} 0 
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
		  -x+2y-4z {}={} 0
		</mrow>
	      </md>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\xvec = x_3\threevec{-2}{1}1</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\xvec = x_2\threevec{0}{1}{0} +
	      x_3\threevec{-2}01</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
	  
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Explain your responses to these questions.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that <m>\vvec</m> is orthogonal to both
	      <m>\wvec_1</m> and <m>\wvec_2</m>.  Can you guarantee
	      that <m>\vvec</m> is also orthogonal to any linear
	      combination <m>c_1\wvec_1+c_2\wvec_2</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that <m>\vvec</m> is orthogonal to itself.  What
	      can you say about <m>\vvec</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
	      
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p> Yes, because <m>\vvec\cdot(c_1\wvec_1+c_2\wvec_2) =
	    c_1\vvec\cdot\wvec_1 + c_2\vvec\cdot\wvec_2 = 0</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec = \len{\vvec}^2 = 0</m> so
	      <m>\vvec=\zerovec</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p> Yes
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec=\zerovec</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Suppose that <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and
	<m>\vvec_3</m> form a basis for <m>\real^3</m> and that each
	vector is orthogonal to the other two.  Suppose also that
	<m>\vvec</m> is another vector in <m>\real^3</m>.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Explain why
	      <m>\vvec=c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2+c_3\vvec_3</m> for some
	      scalars <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, and <m>c_3</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Beginning with the expression
	      <me>
		\vvec\cdot\vvec_1 =
		(c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2+c_3\vvec_3)\cdot\vvec_1,
	      </me>
	      apply the distributive property of dot products to
	      explain why
	      <me>
		c_1=\frac{\vvec\cdot\vvec_1}{\vvec_1\cdot\vvec_1}.
	      </me>
	      Find similar expressions for <m>c_2</m> and <m>c_3</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Verify that
	      <me>
		\vvec_1=\threevec121,\hspace{24pt}
		\vvec_2=\threevec1{-1}1,\hspace{24pt}
		\vvec_3=\threevec10{-1}
	      </me>
	      form a basis for <m>\real^3</m> and that each vector is
	      orthogonal to the other two.  Use what you've discovered
	      in this problem to write the vector
	      <m>\vvec=\threevec35{-1}</m> as a linear combination of
	      <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
		
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Since <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m>
	      form a basis for <m>\real^3</m>, any vector in
	      <m>\real^3</m> can be written as a linear combination of
	      them.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec\cdot\vvec_1 = c_1\vvec_1\cdot\vvec_1</m> so
	      that
	      <m>c_1 =
	      \frac{\vvec\cdot\vvec_1}{\vvec_1\cdot\vvec_1}</m>.
	    </p>
	    <p>
	      In the same way,
	      <m>c_2 =
	      \frac{\vvec\cdot\vvec_2}{\vvec_2\cdot\vvec_2}</m> and
	      <m>c_3 =
	      \frac{\vvec\cdot\vvec_3}{\vvec_3\cdot\vvec_3}</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Check that the vectors are orthogonal by computing their
	      dot products.  Then
	      <m>\vvec = 2\vvec_1 - \vvec_2 + 2\vvec_3</m> by
	      computing the ratios of dot products.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Since <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m>
	      form a basis for <m>\real^3</m>, any vector in
	      <m>\real^3</m> can be written as a linear combination of
	      them.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Apply the distributive property.
	    </p>
	    <p>
	      <m>c_2 =
	      \frac{\vvec\cdot\vvec_2}{\vvec_2\cdot\vvec_2}</m> and
	      <m>c_3 =
	      \frac{\vvec\cdot\vvec_3}{\vvec_3\cdot\vvec_3}</m> 
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\vvec = 2\vvec_1 - \vvec_2 + 2\vvec_3</m> 
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>
	

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Suppose that <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and
	<m>\vvec_3</m> are three nonzero vectors that are pairwise
	orthogonal;  that is, each vector is orthogonal to the other
	two.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Explain why <m>\vvec_3</m> cannot be a linear
	      combination of <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Explain why this set of three vectors is 
	      linearly independent.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>\vvec_3 = c_1\vvec_1 + c_2\vvec_2</m>, then <m>c_1
	      = \frac{\vvec_3\cdot\vvec_1}{\vvec_1\cdot\vvec_2} =
	      0</m>.  In the same way, <m>c_2=0</m> so <m>\vvec_3</m>
	      must be the zero vector.  We're told, however, that
	      <m>\vvec_3</m> is nonzero.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      We've seen that <m>\vvec_3</m> is not a linear
	      combination of <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m>.  The
	      same thinking shows that none of the vectors is a linear
	      combination of the others so they form a linearly
	      independent set.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>\vvec_3 = c_1\vvec_1 + c_2\vvec_2</m>, then
	      <m>c_1=0</m> and <m>c_2=0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      None of the vectors is a linear
	      combination of the others.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	In the next chapter, we will consider certain <m>n\times n</m>
	matrices <m>A</m> and define a function
	<me>
	  q(\xvec) = \xvec\cdot(A\xvec),
	</me>
	where <m>\xvec</m> is a vector in <m>\real^n</m>.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that
	      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}
	      1 \amp 2 \\
	      2 \amp 1 \\
	      \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\xvec=\twovec21</m>.  Evaluate
	      <m>q(\xvec) = \xvec\cdot(A\xvec)</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      For a general vector <m>\xvec=\twovec xy</m>, evaluate
	      <m>q(\xvec) = \xvec\cdot(A\xvec)</m> as an expression
	      involving <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that <m>\vvec</m> is an eigenvector of a matrix
	      <m>A</m> with associated eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> and
	      that <m>\vvec</m> has length 1.  What is the value of
	      the function <m>q(\xvec)</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\xvec) = 13</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\xvec) = x^2 + 4xy + y^2</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\vvec) = \vvec\cdot(A\vvec) =
	      \lambda\vvec\cdot\vvec = \lambda</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\xvec) = 13</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\xvec) = x^2 + 4xy + y^2</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\vvec) = \lambda</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Back in <xref ref="sec-expect" />,
	we saw that equations of the 
	form <m>Ax+By = C</m> represent lines in the plane.  In this
	exercise, we will see how this expression arises
	geometrically.
	<figure xml:id ="fig-ex-eq-line">
	  <sidebyside width="50%">
	    <image source = "images/ex-eq-line" />
	  </sidebyside>
	  <caption>
	    A line, a point <m>\pvec</m> on the line, and a vector
	    <m>\nvec</m> perpendicular to the line.
	  </caption>
	</figure>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Find the slope and vertical intercept of the line shown
	      in <xref ref="fig-ex-eq-line" />.  Then write an
	      equation for the line in the form 
	      <m>y=mx+b</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Suppose that <m>\pvec</m> is a point on the line, that
	      <m>\nvec</m> is a vector perpendicular to the line, and 
	      that <m>\xvec=\twovec xy</m> is a general
	      point on the line.  Sketch the vector <m>\xvec-\pvec</m>
	      and describe the angle between this vector and the vector
	      <m>\nvec</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What is the value of the dot product <m>\nvec\cdot(\xvec
	      - \pvec)</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Explain why the equation of the line can be written in
	      the form <m>\nvec\cdot\xvec = \nvec\cdot\pvec</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Identify the vectors <m>\pvec</m> and <m>\nvec</m> for
	      the line illustrated in <xref ref="fig-ex-eq-line" />
	      and use them to write the equation of the line in terms
	      of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.  Verify that this expression
	      is algebraically equivalent to the equation
	      <m>y=mx+b</m> that you earlier found for this line.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Explain why any line in the plane can be described by an
	      equation having the form <m>Ax+By = C</m>.  What is the
	      significance of the vector <m>\twovec AB</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The slope <m>m=-1/2</m> and the intercept <m>b=3</m> so
	      <m>y=3-x/2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The vector <m>\xvec-\pvec</m> is in the direction of the
	      line so it is orthogonal to <m>\nvec</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Since these vectors are orthogonal, their dot product is
	      <m>0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Since <m>\nvec\cdot(\xvec-\pvec) = 0</m>, we have
	      <m>\nvec\cdot\xvec - \nvec\cdot\pvec = 0</m>, which
	      implies that <m>\nvec\cdot\xvec = \nvec\cdot\pvec</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\pvec=\twovec22</m> and <m>\nvec=\twovec12</m>.  This
	      gives <m>x+2y = 6</m>.  We can rearrange this to have
	      the form <m>y=3-x/2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If we choose a vector <m>\nvec=\twovec{A}{B}</m> that is
	      perpendicular to the line and a point <m>\pvec</m> on
	      the line, we have <m>\nvec\cdot\xvec = Ax + By =
	      \nvec\cdot\pvec = C</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>y=3-x/2</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\xvec-\pvec</m> is orthogonal to <m>\nvec</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>0</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Apply the distributive property
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>x+2y = 6</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>\nvec=\twovec{A}{B}</m> is
	      perpendicular to the line.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
		
  </exercise>
      
</exercises>
